definition.value: A zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the phosphate to the amino group of any ceramide phosphoethanolamine.

Any of a class of phosphosphingolipids in which the amino group of a sphingoid base is in amide linkage with one of several fatty acids, while the terminal hydroxy group of the sphingoid base is esterified to phosphorylethanolamine.

label.value: EC 3.6.* (hydrolases acting on acid anhydrides) inhibitor

definition.value: Any hydrolase inhibitor that interferes with the action of a hydrolase which acts on acid anhydrides (EC 3.6.*.*).
A cyclooxygenase inhibitor that interferes with the action of cyclooxygenase 3.
A mancude heterobicyclic organic group consisting of a benzene ring fused to a pyrrole ring.
Any organic molecule containing a C#C bond.
An acetylenic compound which a carbon of the C#C moiety is attached to a hydrogen atom.
A dipeptide composed of glycine and L-tyrosine joined by a peptide linkage.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-serine residues.
A bicyclic organic group that contains both carbon and hetero atoms.
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-phenylalanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and glycine residues.
An L-alpha-amino acid which is biosynthesised from erythrose 4-phosphate and phosphoenolpyruvate (i.e. phenylalanine, tyrosine, and tryptophan). A closed class.

A carbonyl compound produced as a water-soluble byproduct when fatty acids are broken down for energy in the liver. There are three endogenous ketone bodies: acetone, acetoacetic acid, and (R)-3-hydroxybutyric acid; others may be produced as a result of the metabolism of synthetic triglycerides.
A fatty amide obtained by the formal condensation of (11Z)-eicosaenoic acid with ethanolamine.
A dipeptide formed from L-alanyl and L-leucine residues.
A peptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of Gly-Pro.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-O-acyl group is specified as arachidonoyl.
A dipeptide formed from L-arginine and L-phenylalanine residues. It exhibits vasorelaxant activity.
A 1-O-(alk-1-enyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alk-1-enyl group contains 16 carbons and no additional double bonds.
A  lysophosphatidylcholine P-16:0 in which the alk-1-enyl group is hexadec-1-en-1-yl.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:0 in which the acyl substituent is located at position 1 and is specified as stearoyl.
An antimetabolite that impairs the action of folic acids
A dipeptide formed from glycine and L-tryptophan residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-histidine and L-valine residues.
An alpha-amino-acid residue derived from S-palmitoyl-L-cysteine.
An  EC 1.17.* (oxidoreductase acting on CH or CH2) inhibitor that inhibits the action of ribonucleoside-diphosphate reductase (EC 1.17.4.1).
A lactam in which the amide bond is contained within a five-membered ring, which includes the amide nitrogen and the carbonyl carbon.
A pyrrolidinone in which the oxo group is at position 2 of the pyrrolidine ring.
An optically active form of glyceric acid having L-configuration.
A dipeptide formed from L-isoleucine and L-valine residues.
A D-alpha-amino acid zwitterion that is D-valine in which a proton has been transferred from the carboxy group to the amino group. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
A peptide zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the carboxy to the amino terminus of Ala-Leu.
An organic heterotetracyclic compound that is the 9- epimer of 4'-demethylpodophyllotoxin.
An antagonist at the epidermal growth factor receptor.
A role borne by a molecule that acts to counteract or neutralize the deleterious effects of paracetamol (acetaminophen).
A dipeptide formed from L-leucine and L-glutamic acid residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-lysine and L-leucine residues.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine(1-) that is the conjugate base of 1-oleoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoserine.
An optically active form of O(4)-phosphonatotyrosine(2-) having D-configuration.
A compound that causes the contraction of body tissues, typically used to reduce bleeding from minor abrasions.
A dipeptide formed from L-serine and L-leucine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-threonine and L-phenylalanine residues.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate(2-) obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 1-arachidonoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphate.
An organophosphate oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phospho and carboxy groups as well as protonation of the amino group of O(4)-phosphotyrosine
A non-proteinogenic alpha-amino acid that is tyrosine phosphorylated at the phenolic hydroxy group.
A D-tyrosine derivative that is D-tyrosine phosphorylated at the phenolic hydroxy group.
A dipeptide formed from L-valine and L-leucine residues.
An organofluorine compound and antineoplastic agent, used as its mesylate salt in treatment of metastatic melanoma.
A serine/threonine kinase inhibitor that specifically inhibits human mutant serine/threonine kinase (B-Raf)
